    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.35c.15"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>December 7, 1971</dateline>
                    
                    <note>Ans.1-18-72</note>
                   
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>University of Nebraska Press</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Lincoln, Nebraska</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am a young wmoan of twenty-five who admires you a great deal. The books I have read, <hi rend="underline">Black Elk Speaks</hi>, <hi rend="underline">The Spenldid Wayfaring</hi>, and <hi rend="underline">A Cycle of the West</hi>, are beautiful works of art that become more enjoyable with each new reading.</p> 
                
                <p>It seems to me, Mr. Neihardt, that such awe-inspiring lands as the Black Hills and the Big Horn Mountains have so much power and mystery that they could never be diminished by the marks of man's "progress." Yet what majesty they must have had when the Great Spirit and his people lived in them. It is your fine portrayal of that spirit of the land itself, as well as the Indians' regard for it, that makes your work so appealing to me.</p> 
                
                <p>I wonder if you could answer a couple of questions. First, according to Black Elk, Jack Wilson was the Wasichus' name for the Wanekia, son of the Great Spirit. What is known of this man and his life? Was he sincere?</p> 
                
                <p>Also, regarding your own life, did you know Charlie Russell, the Montana painter? His scenes depicted the lands and the people of the upper Missouri River, and they were painted between the 1880's and 1926. (I, myself, am a painter who's<sic>whose</sic> ambition is to live and work in the Rocky Mountains.) Did you know any other artists of the Old West?</p> 
                
                <p>I'd also like to have a list of your published work. My best wishes and a Merry Christmas to you, Mr. Neihardt.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours truly,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Cheryl Roark</signed>
                    <signed>(Miss) Cheryl Roark</signed> 
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>13160 <hi rend="caps">W.</hi> Outer Drive, Apt. 307</addrLine>      
                        <addrLine>Detroit, Michigan 48223</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
                <fw>2</fw>
                
            </div1>
